  "prompt": "Why is glass called a super-cooled liquid?",
  "response": "The term \"super-cooled liquid\" when applied to glass is a bit of a misnomer and stems from historical misunderstandings about the nature of glass. Glass is actually an amorphous solid, meaning it has a disordered atomic structure unlike crystalline solids, but it behaves mechanically like a solid.\n\nHistorically, glass was often described as a super-cooled liquid because it does not crystallize as it cools from its molten state, and its molecules are arranged in a disordered, liquid-like manner. This led to the misconception that glass flows over time, which contributed to the idea that it might be a super-cooled liquid.\n\nModern materials science has clarified that glass is an amorphous solid. While it does not have a long-range ordered crystal structure, it does not flow over time at room temperature. The belief that old window panes are thicker at the bottom due to glass flow has been debunked; such panes were often thicker at the bottom simply because of the methods used to manufacture and install them.\n\nIn summary, though glass exhibits some characteristics of liquids at the molecular level, it is correctly classified as an amorphous solid. The term \"super-cooled liquid\" is outdated and not scientifically accurate.",
